item.title: The secret world of microwave networks
item.excerpt: Stretching between London and Frankfurt there is a private, mysterious network that is twice as fast as the normal Internet. The connection, provided by a series of microwave dishes on masts, was once completely secret: only one very rich company was allowed to use it, and no one else knew about it.

images.caption: Enlarge / A 1949 newspaper clipping showing AT&T's "just 34 hops" microwave link from New York to Chicago.
Enlarge / The UK's proposed microwave backbone in 1956.

Enlarge / A map of some of the microwave networks in southern England and continental Europe, mapped out by Alexandre Laumonier. The microwave links down to Cornwall are for the transatlantic submarine cables that land there. This map is by no means exhaustive; it was compiled by a third party.
Enlarge / The BridgeWave FP80-3000, capable of up to 3Gbps over 80GHz. For scale, the antenna is 30cm across.
Enlarge / One of BT's many microwave towers, on top of a hill somewhere.
